What is the structure of your dataset?¶

  • Month 1-4(The first quarter of the year,and This column has been converted to categorical to make it easier to read through visualization).
  • Year2008 (I deleted this column because it is only one year).
  • DayOfWeek 1-7(This column has been converted to categorical to make it easier to read through visualization).
  • ArrTime actual arrival time.
  • UniqueCarrier unique carrier code.
  • CRSDepTime scheduled departure time.
  • CRSArrTime scheduled arrival time .
  • DepDelay Departure delay,in minutes.
  • ArrDelay arrival delay,in minutes.
  • Dest destination IATA airport code.
  • Distance in miles.
  • Cancelled was the flight cancelled(This column has been converted to "bool").
  • CancellationCode reason for cancellation (A = carrier, B = weather, C =National Air System, D = security).
  • CarrierDelay in minutes: Carrier delay is within the control of the air carrier.
  • WeatherDelay Delay due to weather conditions.
  • NASDelay in minutes.
  • SecurityDelay in minutes.
  • LateAircraftDelay in minutes.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

  • Departure delay.
  • UniqueCarrier unique carrier code.
  • Cancelled.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

  • Arrival delay.
  • Month.
  • Day of the week.
  • CarrierDelay.
  • CancellationCode reason for cancellation. ### Our goal in this report is to answer some questions such as:
  • What is the percentage of canceled flights in the first quarter of 2008?
  • Which airline has the highest flights in the first quarter?
  • What is the shape of the distribution of delay departure? Are there any interesting values? What is the distribution of the most values?
  • What are the most common reasons for canceling flights?
  • Which airline has the highest number of flight cancellations?
  • Which airline has the highest average delay due to the carrier?
  • What is the day with the least average delay for departure and arrival?
  • What is the month with the least average delay in departure and arrival?
  • What does the average departure delay look like according to the days of the week and month from the first quarter of 2008?
  • With the heat map and relationship detection, are interesting relationships observed in the data set of interest?

bin_edges = np.arange(flights_df['DepDelay'].min(), flights_df['DepDelay'].max()+2, 10)

# set the x values limitation for the for a magnified distribution plot. I start at the min() and use 250 as the right limit

# Set labels names

What does the average departure delay look like according to the days of the week and month from the first quarter of 2008?¶

In [34]:
#Visualize Average departure delay by Month and day of week
# Set the size
fig = plt.figure(figsize=[23,8])
# set the title
fig.suptitle('Average departure delay by Month and day of week', fontsize=18)

ax = sb.barplot(data = flights_df, x = 'Month', y = 'DepDelay', hue = 'DayOfWeek')
ax.legend(loc='center left', bbox_to_anchor=(1, 0.5), title = 'Day of Week')
# Set labels names
ax.set_xlabel("Departure Delays in Minutes - per month",fontsize=17)
ax.set_ylabel("Number of delays in Minutes",fontsize=17);

Observation:

  • We notice that Friday is the most day that people having flights on in the first quarter of the year.
  • Note in March, weekends have a high average delay.
  • February has a high average delay, except for Thursday and Saturday.
  • April has the lowest average delay in the first quarter on all days of the week except Friday.

With the heat map and relationship detection, are interesting relationships observed in the data set of interest?¶

plt.figure(figsize=[8,5])

We see that there is a high correlation between the arrival delay and departure delay.also, high correlation between the scheduled arrival time and scheduled departure time , Which is logically expected.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. Were there features that strengthened each other in terms of looking at your feature(s) of interest?¶

  • Through the bar chart, we noticed a positive relationship between the delay of arrival time and the delay of departure, whether it was for the days of the week or months in the first quarter.
  • From the clustered bar chart , we see that Wednesdays usually have the lowest average departure delays, and Fridays the highest average departures delays in the first quarter of the year.

Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?¶

As we can see above, there is a significant correlation between arrival delay and departure delay. There is also an average correlation between carrier delay, arrival delay and departure delay. however,It looks like there aren't so many correlations between the quantitative features. But we observed so much detailed information when utilizing it with other features.
